snippet.textDisplay:
I think the moral of the story was supposed to be "there are some things you are better off not knowing"


and from an outside meta perspective, there is no way "we" as an audience can know what they saw, because the writers don't "know" what they saw anymore than we as an audience can know what was in the pulp fiction briefcase.

whatever it is, is beyond human comprehension, which is why it affects rick and jerry so strongly . the cat begged them not to ask questions and the persisted they asked questions and the answer they got drove them to the brink of insanity.

the lesson is that they should have just left well enough alone.

snippet.textDisplay:
BROOO, this video and your idea reminds me of my first (brilliant) philosophy class. It talked about what philosophy is, by breaking down the word. Philo means wisdom, and sophy comes from the goddess sophia and is usually translated as ‘love of’. So philosophy is the love of wisdom. The point my professor made was that it isn’t love for wisdom, as in love for having wisdom. Having the wisdom stops the covetting, the wanting of wisdom, and this is not the point of philosophy. It is about keeping the wisdom at a distance. To keep the flirtatious dance of love going by not owning. It is about the continuous asking of questions, that lead to more questions, that lead to more questions. Once answers are made we enter the realm of the logos, or the knowing (examples bioLOGY, or psychoLOGY. Both deriving from philosophy, as is every other science). We lose the flirtation or the distance; the thing that makes love exciting. The episode reminds me of this point.

Tl;dr video explains philosophy
